Stack memory - variables (local), function data call. LIFO (Last In First Out). 
void functionExample() {
    int x = 10; // x is stored in the stack memory
}

Heap memory - for pointers basically. Dynamic memory, and be changed in size. In C++ we use "new" keyword for creating dynamic objects.
void functionExample() {
    int* p = new int; // dynamically allocated int in heap memory
    *p = 10;
    // more code
    delete p; // deallocate memory
}

Data segment - two parts: initialized data dn uninitialized data.
// Initialized data segment
int globalVar = 10; // global variables
static int staticVar = 10; // static local variables
const int constVar = 10; // constant variables with value

// Uninitialized data segment
int globalVar; // uninitialized global variables

Code segment - executable code that you as the developer write for machine to compile 
void functionExample() {
    // The machine code for this function is stored in the code segment.
}